<HR NOSHADE>
<H2>
ECONOMIC COMMENTARY</H2>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 >
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSTART="1"><IMG SRC="earnpershare.gif" ></TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP COLSTART="2">
<H4>
Stagflation is a term we have not heard in quite some time. Recall that
it is a term which was coined in the 1970s to describe the phenomenon of
stagnate economic growth with high unemployment and accelerating inflation.
Perhaps we should lament the decline in "wordsmithing" as the best phrase
we have been able to conjure up for the opposite of "stagflation" is a
"Goldilocks economy." The point is that the "New Paradigm" of high growth
with low unemployment and near price stability we have been hearing so
much about isn't new at all. It is simply the converse of the stagflation
of the 1970s. After the experience of the '70s, we already knew that the
contemporaneous, or near term correlation between employment/growth and
inflation, the Phillips Curve, was weak at best.
<BR>
<br>
Rather, it appears that we are seeing the results of some tough decisions
made in the late '80s regarding the restructuring of the private as well
as the public sector. And for those of us old enough to remember hiding
under our school desks during air raid drills, the collapse of the Soviet
Union and the subsequent decline in our defense spending should not be
overlooked as a major contributor to declining inflation.
<BR>
<br>
But what about the future of inflation? For answers to that question we
must look back to the early part of this decade. Five years ago, on September
30, 1992, the yield on the 90-day T-bill was 2.74%; the 5-year T-note,
5.32%; and the 30-year T-bond, 7.38%. At quarter end '97, the yields were
5.09%, 5.99%, and 6.40%, respectively. Five years ago the yield curve,
the plot of interest rates from overnight to 30 years, had not been so
steep for nearly a half century in relative terms. The yield on an intermediate
maturity was double that of a short-term T-bill, and a long-term Bond returned
nearly half as much as an intermediate Note. This was the midpoint in an
approximately 2-year period of extraordinary liquidity creation for the
financial system by the Federal Reserve. The steepness of the yield curve
is a key indicator of the level of liquidity in an economy, as well as
inflation expectations to some degree. The Federal Reserve made it possible
for some large financial intermediaries to borrow short and invest long
at extraordinarily wide spreads in order to rebuild their balance sheets
that were severely damaged in the late '80s and early '90s.</H4>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 >
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSTART="1"><IMG SRC="nonperformallow.gif" ></TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP COLSTART="2">
<H4>
The Federal Reserve withdrew some of that liquidity in 1994, causing one
of the sharpest declines in fixed income securities prices in many years.
But much of the liquidity has remained in the financial system. The system
itself has created enormous additional liquidity on its own through increased
valuations of equity securities, the rebound in real estate prices, and
increased lending by financial intermediaries. In the third quarter, for
example, an important indicator of economic growth, Commercial and Industrial
Loans, increased at nearly a 10% pace. This indicates very strong growth
for the third quarter and likely the fourth quarter as well.
<BR>
<br>
Economic weakness in the economies of our major trading partners, Europe
and Japan, has kept a lid on pricing power domestically. The memory of
massive corporate downsizing has kept worker demand in check until recently.
However, Europe appears to be rebounding to the point that the German Central
Bank saw fit to raise key interest rates to slow credit expansion. The
UPS strike settlement could be viewed as a turning point in labor compensation.
Ironically, the once vaunted Japanese economy still struggles.
<br>
<br>
 Close inspection may reveal that the people who suggested that the Japanese economic model
was to be emulated by all are the same people who are saying inflation
is dead. The flat yield curve relative to 1992, with a relatively passive
Federal Reserve, seems to indicate a high degree of investor confidence
that inflation will not be an issue well into the future. A "New Paradigm"
or just another chapter in economic history?</H4>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<HR NOSHADE>
<H2>
QUARTERLY HIGHLIGHTS</H2>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="chain.gif" ></CENTER>

<CENTER><TABLE CELLPADDING=10 >
<TR ALIGN=left VALIGN=left>
<TD VALIGN=TOP COLSTART="1">
<h4>
<h3>Buying a car can be a tedious and often confusing process.</h3> <h4>On September
2, 1997, Keystone Financial, Inc. introduced KeyBuySM, a customized research
and auto loan service designed to take the worry and frustration out of
buying a new car. The first direct auto loan service of its kind to be
offered by banks in the Keystone market area, KeyBuy allows customers to
research the car they want to buy, apply for an auto loan, and get assistance
with their trade-in vehicle, all on-line at www.keyfin.com. Or, customers
may call a KeyBuy Associate toll-free at 1-888-4-KEYBUY.
<BR>
<br>
KeyBuy handles those things that buyers don't have the time or desire to
do themselves. KeyBuy helps the customer find the right car through a series
of simple, intuitive questions. For example, a customer can demand that
a car have a sunroof (thereby ranking cars with sunroofs higher than those
without). The guide generates a personally ranked list of cars. The customer
can then obtain a detailed, side-by-side comparison of the cars on the
list.
<BR>
<br>
After finding the right car, a customer can calculate payments and fill
out a loan application on-line. Once approved, KeyBuy financing includes
a sight draft (which works like a check) that the customer can take to
a dealer. This permits buyers to negotiate with the power of cash and purchase
the vehicle of their choice, right on the spot.
<BR>
<br>
This new direct auto loan service package further reinforces Keystone's
commitment to Relationship Banking.
<BR>
<br>
For more information on KeyBuy, call 1-888-4-KEYBUY or visit our Web site
at www.keyfin.com.</H4>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

